Breast cancer analysis

Emma Busarello, Gabriele Berrera, Francesco Penasa

Introduction

Cancer is a complicated disease with each individual tumor exhibiting to a variable degree a set of overlapping phenotypes that include abnormal proliferation and cell survival, genetic instability, tissue invasion, metastasis and angiogenesis. In particular, breast cancer is the most common cancer among women worldwide, representing nearly a quarter (25%) of all cancers with an estimated 2.1 million new cancer cases diagnosed in 2018 (Malvia et al.,). Understanding of deregulated gene expression is therefore an essential goal for cancer research because unraveling this problem will provide insights into the fundamental nature of cancer as well as provide opportunities for therapeutic intervention (Ellis M.J).

Analysis

RNA-seq count data extracted from TCGA* breast cancer dataset were loaded in RStudio for the analysis. From the original TCGA data only 50 cases (tumor samples) and 50 controls (normal samples) were selected.

https://www.cancer.gov/about-nci/organization/ccg/research/structural-genomics/tcga

The following three dataframes are available:
  • raw_counts_df = contains the raw RNA-seq counts
  • c_anno_df = contains sample name and condition (Case and Control).
  • r_anno_df = contains the ENSEMBL genes ids, the length of the genes and the genes symbols

Only protein coding genes were extracted for subsequent analysis

r_anno_df<-r_anno_df[which(r_anno_df$gene_biotype=="protein_coding"),]
raw_counts_df <- raw_counts_df[which(rownames(raw_counts_df)%in%r_anno_df$ensembl_gene_id),]

Raw counts data were filtered retaining only genes with a raw count >20 in at least 1 Case and 1 Control sample

count_thr <- 20
repl_thr <- 2 
filter_vec <- apply(raw_counts_df,1,function(y)
                    max(by(y, c_anno_df$condition, function(x) sum(x>=count_thr))))

filter_counts_df <- raw_counts_df[filter_vec>=repl_thr,]
filter_anno_df <- r_anno_df[rownames(filter_counts_df),]

Differential expression analysis

Differential expression analysis was performed using edgeR package

library("edgeR")
## Loading required package: limma

Up- and down-regulated genes were selected using a p-value cutoff of 0.01, a log fold change ratio >1.5 for up-regulated genes and < (-1.5) for down-regulated genes and a log2 CPM >1.

Create a DGRList object

edge_c <- DGEList(counts=filter_counts_df,group=c_anno_df$condition,
                  samples=c_anno_df,genes=filter_anno_df) 
edge_n <- calcNormFactors(edge_c,method="TMM")  ## Normalization with edgeR (TMM method)

Display normalization factors

norm_factors <- mean(edge_n$samples$lib.size*edge_n$samples$norm.factors)/
  (edge_n$samples$lib.size*edge_n$samples$norm.factors)
names(norm_factors) <- edge_n$samples$sample

Create a cpm-rpkm table (normalized expression values)

cpm_table <- as.data.frame(round(cpm(edge_n),2))

Define the experimental design matrix

design <- model.matrix(~0+group, data=edge_c$samples)
colnames(design) <- levels(edge_c$samples$group)
rownames(design) <- edge_c$samples$sample

Calculate dispersion and fit with edgeR

edge_d <- estimateDisp(edge_n,design)
edge_f <- glmQLFit(edge_d,design)

The function edgeRglmQLF performs differential analysis with edgeR

edgeRglmQLF <- function(mat=edge_f,contro,cpm_mat=edge_n,label="",sig_thr=0.5,sig_col="CPM",
                        fc_thr=0.5,pval_col="p_val",pval_thr=0.05,names=FALSE)
{
  degs <- glmQLFTest(edge_f,contrast=contro)$table[,-3]
  colnames(degs) <- c("log2_FC","log2_CPM","p_val")
  a_levels <- rownames(contro)[which(contro!=0)]
  a_samples <- which(cpm_mat$samples$group%in%a_levels)
  cpm_sele <- cpm(cpm_mat,log=T)[,a_samples]
  degs$log2_CPM <- apply(cpm_sele,1,function(x) mean(x))
  #degs<-exactTest(edge_c, pair=cond, dispersion=bcv^2)$table
  degs$p_adj <- p.adjust(degs$p_val, method ="BH")
  degs$class <- "="
  degs[which(degs[,sig_col]>=sig_thr & degs$log2_FC>=fc_thr & degs[,pval_col]<=pval_thr),
       "class"] <- "+"
  degs[which(degs[,sig_col]>=sig_thr & degs$log2_FC<=(-fc_thr) & degs[,pval_col]<=pval_thr),
       "class"] <- "-"
  degs$class <- as.factor(degs$class)
  degs$comp <- label
  degs$id <- rownames(degs)
  degs <- degs[,c("id","comp","log2_FC","log2_CPM","p_val","p_adj","class")]
  if(names=="TRUE"){
    newnames <- paste(label,colnames(degs),sep="_")
    colnames(degs) <- newnames
  }
  return(degs)
}

The function is applied in order to identify differentially expressed genes

contro <- makeContrasts("Case-Control", levels=design) ## definition of the contrast
DEGs <- edgeRglmQLF(mat=edge_f, cpm_mat=edge_n, contro=contro,label = "Control-case",
                    sig_thr=1, sig_col="log2_CPM", fc_thr=1.5, pval_thr=0.01, 
                    pval_col="p_adj",names=F)
head(DEGs[order(DEGs$p_adj),])

Gene Set Enrichment Analysis

Both GO and KEGG gene set enrichment analysis were performed using the package clusterProfiler. From the list of differentially expressed genes two new lists were created, the first containing the up-regulated and the second the down-regulated genes.

upDEGs <- DEGs %>% filter(class == "+")
downDEGs <- DEGs %>% filter(class == "-")

GO analysis

The GO analysis was performed first with the Biological Process group (BP):

# GO analysis for the up-regulated genes
up_ego_BP <- enrichGO(gene = upDEGs$external_gene_name,     
                   OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db,
                   keyType = 'SYMBOL',
                   ont = "BP",
                   pAdjustMethod = "BH",
                   pvalueCutoff = 0.05,
                   qvalueCutoff = 0.05)

# GO analysis for the down-regulated genes
down_ego_BP <- enrichGO(gene = downDEGs$external_gene_name,
                      OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db,
                      keyType = 'SYMBOL',
                      ont = "BP",
                      pAdjustMethod = "BH",
                      pvalueCutoff = 0.05,
                      qvalueCutoff = 0.05)

And then with the Molecular Function group:

# GO analysis for the up-regulated genes
up_ego_MF <- enrichGO(gene = upDEGs$external_gene_name,     
                      OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db,
                      keyType = 'SYMBOL',
                      ont = "MF",
                      pAdjustMethod = "BH",
                      pvalueCutoff = 0.05,
                      qvalueCutoff = 0.05)

# GO analysis for the down-regulated genes
down_ego_MF <- enrichGO(gene = downDEGs$external_gene_name,
                        OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db,
                        keyType = 'SYMBOL',
                        ont = "MF",
                        pAdjustMethod = "BH",
                        pvalueCutoff = 0.05,
                        qvalueCutoff = 0.05)

Motifs Analysis

We identified which transcription factors were enriched in the promoters of all up-regulated genes. First, all the promoter sequences were retrieved using the function getSequence, setting a window of 500 nucleotides upstream for each gene.

promoter_seq <- getSequence(id = upDEGs$id, 
                            type="ensembl_gene_id",
                            seqType="gene_flank",
                            upstream=500,
                            mart=ensembl)

Then the motif enrichment analysis was performed using the function motifEnrichment:

data(PWMLogn.hg19.MotifDb.Hsap)
sequences <- lapply(promoter_seq$gene_flank,function(x) DNAString(x))
enriched_TFs <- motifEnrichment(sequences,PWMLogn.hg19.MotifDb.Hsap,score = "affinity")

The resulting enriched transcription factors can be visualized in a fansy way using the function groupReport:

report = groupReport(enriched_TFs)

In the next figure are plotted the top 5 enriched transcription factors resulted from our analysis:

From these top 5 motifs we selected only one of them (we selected the fourth one: BHLHA15) and we computed the empirical distributions of scores. For the selected transcription factor we searched for all PWMs in MotifDB:

selected_tf = report$target[4]

tfs_motifs = subset(MotifDb, organism=='Hsapiens' & geneSymbol==selected_tf)
PWM = toPWM(as.list(tfs_motifs))
For the selected TF we found 3 PWMs:
  • Hsapiens-cisbp_1.02-M5304_1.02
  • Hsapiens-jolma2013-BHLHA15
  • Hsapiens-SwissRegulon-BHLHA15.SwissRegulon

Then the empirical distribution using the function motifEcdf:

ecdf = motifEcdf(PWM,organism = "hg19",quick=TRUE)

With this function a distribution is associated at each PWM:

Then for each motif were caluated the scores with a cutoff theshold of 99.5%

thresholds = lapply(ecdf,function(x) quantile(x,0.995))
scores = motifScores(sequences,PWM,raw.score=FALSE,cutoff=unlist(thresholds))

Here are reported the calculated scores for each PWM of the first 10 motifs:

Using this table of scores were then selected only those genes having a region in their promoter with binding scores above the computed thresholds for any of the previously selected PWMs.

genes_positions <- which(apply(scores,1,function(x){sum(x==0)})==0)
genes_id <- promoter_seq$ensembl_gene_id[genes_positions]

Results

By performing this analysis we were able to extract some significant information from the RNA-seq data of the patients. In particular, we found the differential expressed genes, distinguished in up- and down-regulated. Computing the GSEA we looked at the the terms and pathways that have become enriched in the breast cancer tumor patients, finding alterations for example in:
  • Biological Processes: the most over-represented biological processes are related with the cell cycle: chromosome segregation, nuclear division, organelle fission, etc. Deregulation of the cell cycle is a hallmark of cancer that enables limitless cell division. To support this malignant phenotype, cells acquire molecular alterations that abrogate or bypass control mechanisms in signaling pathways and cellular checkpoints that normally function to prevent genomic instability and uncontrolled cell proliferation (Thu et al.,) Some of the most under-represented processes are related with extracellular matrix (ECM): cell-substrate adhesion, extracellular structure organization, extracellular matrix organization, etc. The ECM constitutes a complex of structural proteins and its reorganization is essential during cancer progression. These proteins provide biochemical signals to promote metastasis progression of cancer to advanced stage. In addition, various ECM proteins such as integrins, collagen and fibronectin engage in cell adhesion, invasion and metastasis (Jena et al.,).
  • Molecular Functions: the most over-represented molecular functions are extracellular matrix structural constituent, glycosaminoglycan binding and heparin binding. Linear glycosaminoglycan (GAG) chains constitute proteoglycans that are expressed on the cell surface, cytoplasm, and extracellular matrix and regulate cell migration, invasion and growth of various cancer cells (Iida et al.,). The up-regulation of heparin-binding growth factors represents a mechanism by which cancer cells can enhance growth factor signaling (Lai et al.,). The most under-represented molecular functions are tubulin binding, microtubulue binding and microtuble motor activity. Microtubules are highly dynamic cytoskeletal fibres that are composed of tubulin subunits and are involved in cell movement, intracellular trafficking, and mitosis.In the context of cancer, the tubulin family of proteins is recognized as the target of the tubulin-binding chemotherapeutics, which suppress the dynamics of the mitotic spindle to cause mitotic arrest and cell death. Changes in microtubule stability and the expression of different tubulin isotypes have been reported for a range of cancers. These changes have been correlated with poor prognosis and chemotherapy resistance.
    Emerging evidence suggests that tubulins and microtubule-associated proteins may play a role in a range of cellular stress responses, thus conferring survival advantage to cancer cells (Parker et al.,)
  • Pathways: the most enriched pathways, resulted from KEEG analysis, are related with the cell cycle and all the signaling pathway regulating it. From the the up-regulated lists of genes, the systemic lupus erythematosus shows a significant result: evidence of possible links between systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) and cancer has generated much interest. Recent studies have shown an increased risk of hematological malignancies and a decreased risk of some reproductive malignancies (Cloutier et al.,). Enriched KEGG pathways resulting from the down-regulated lists of genes are involved in the extracellular signals such as the PI3K-Akt pathway that mediates the effects of a variety of extracellular signals in a number of cellular processes including cell growth, proliferation, and survival.The frequent dysregulation of the PI3K/Akt pathway in breast cancer can increases the activation status of the signaling and can thus lead to cellular transformation (Castaneda et al.,). The engagement of RAS function might be mandatory downstream varied oncogenic alterations for the progression, metastatic dissemination, and therapy resistance in breast cancers (Gali).

By performing motifs analysis, enriched transcription factors involved in breast cancer were identified. Nicotinamide nucleotide transhydrogenase (NNT) has an indispensable role in the homeostasis of NADH and NADPH. The significant contribution of NNT in mitochondrial antioxidant pathways shields cells from oxidative stress. NNT silencing decreases ability of cancer cells to preserve NAD+ and NADPH levels and suppresses their proliferation and aggressive behavior (Gargari et al.,) Metastasis is responsible for a significant number of breast cancer-related deaths. Hypoxia, a primary driving force of cancer metastasis, induces the expression of BHLHE40, a transcription regulator, that promotes tumor cell survival and migration (Sethuraman et al.,).

Conclusion

Whole transcriptome RNA-Seq Analysis enabling us to understand the heterogeneous nature of breast cancer on a genomic level. Genes involved in cell cycle, ECM, metastasis that were found some of the essential pathways found to be up-regulated (according to previous studies). Genes belonging to cell adhesion, cell cycle, ECM receptor interaction pathways were also found deregulated. It is expected that availability of these types of analyses will only increase in the future. It will be imperative that such assays be well validated and have implications for how to modify care for the individual patient.
